Transferring Your Work to a Paris Production Server

This is a step by step instruction list to transfer a working Django project to a Paris production server. This list assumes that your Django project is working correctly with no issues or bugs before it is transferred. It also assumes that you have just been given the Paris instance you are supposed to be using, with no prior installations or knowledge necessary.

1. The first step will be to access your dedicated server instance for the first time, and complete the necessary installations to allow it to work with Django projects. The following steps were taken directly from the Assignment 2 instructions from last semester (with a couple additions for clarity), which walked us through setting up the server for the first time.

- Figure out what your server&#39;s number (###) is? (It should be 3 digits)
- Make sure you are connected to the Internet
- Visit: http://paris.cs.virginia.edu:18### (replace ### with you server&#39;s number)
- You should see a page like this:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

_Note: If the Apache2 page doesn&#39;t display, don&#39;t proceed and post privately on Piazza with the subject (Server not responding)_.

- Now, open the terminal and SSH into your server using the following command:
ssh -p 22### ubuntu@paris.cs.virginia.edu

- Remember to replace the ### above with your server&#39;s number
- Your default password will be given to you by your instructor
- Once you are logged into the server, change your password with the command sudo passwd ubuntu to a passphrase that you don&#39;t mind sharing with your colleagues (don&#39;t use your personal accounts password) and don&#39;t forget what that passphrase is.
- Install virtual environment using the following command:
pip install virtualenv

- Go to the Downloads directory
cd Downloads

- Use the virtualenv command to create a new environment with python3 as the default python version
virtualenv --python=python3 newenv

- The virtualenv has been created, now log into the new environment using the following command:
source newenv/bin/activate

- Install Django 2.1 in the the virtual environment that you created using the following command:
pip install django==2.1

- Go to the &#39;newenv&#39; directory
cd newenv

- Start a new Django project using the following command:
django-admin startproject mysite

- Go to the &#39;mysite&#39; directory
cd mysite

- Again, go to the inner &#39;mysite&#39; directory where &#39;settings.py&#39; is located
cd mysite

- Edit &#39;settings.py&#39; directory
vi settings.py

- Change the
ALLOWED\_HOSTS = []
to
ALLOWED\_HOSTS = [&#39;10.1.1.###&#39;, &#39;128.143.71.210&#39;]
where ### is your server number

- Save the changes in py and exit whatever editor you are using

- Go back up one directory
cd ..

- Run the &#39;manage.py&#39; file using the following command:
python manage.py runserver 10.1.1.###:8000

- Use a your browser and visit http://128.143.71.210:28### where ### is your server number

- You should see a page that looks like this:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- Congratulations, you have completed the first step in getting your server ready for production!
- Once you have confirmed that everything works, go back into the server and delete the temporary project that you just initialized. This can be done by going to the directory that contains the mysite and running the command rm -rf mysite. Make sure to keep this terminal open.

1. Now that your server is ready to put a Django project into production, the next step is to transfer your project onto the server.
  - If you have not already done so, place your project in a GitHub repository so it is accessible outside of just your local machine. Instructions to do this can be found at

[https://help.github.com/en/articles/adding-an-existing-project-to-github-using-the-command-line](https://help.github.com/en/articles/adding-an-existing-project-to-github-using-the-command-line)

1.
  - Open the terminal and make sure that you are currently in the ~/Downloads/newenv directory
  - Clone your project from GitHub, by first copying the clone link from GitHub. You can find the link as seen in the following screeenshot.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- Run the following command in the terminal to clone the project: git clone https://github.com/.../, where the link is what you copied in the previous step. You might have to install git, if it is not on the server already. You will also have to submit your GitHub credentials in order to access the repository.

1. The last step in this process is getting your project up and running now that it is in your production server.
  - First go into the project
cd project\_name

  - Take care of any migration issues that might arise with the following commands
python manage.py makemigrations
python manage.py migrate

  - Go to the inner project\_name directory by using the same command
cd project\_name

1.
  - Edit &#39;settings.py&#39; directory
vi settings.py

  - Change the
ALLOWED\_HOSTS = []
to
ALLOWED\_HOSTS = [&#39;10.1.1.###&#39;, &#39;128.143.71.210&#39;]
where ### is your server number
  - Save the changes in py and exit whatever editor you are using

  - Go back up one directory
cd ..

  - Run the &#39;manage.py&#39; file using the following command:
python manage.py runserver 10.1.1.###:8000

  - Use a your browser and visit http://128.143.71.210:28### where ### is your server number

  - Congratulations, your website is now in production
